Chapter 1
To call
0430 Italy time. Cohren hated waking up that early. He hated it especially because he was responsible for waking up everyone else in his unit. Quietly, he stood up from his bunk, put on his combat uniform, threw on his bulletproof vest and grabbed his belongings from the locker, handling a certain small box carefully. He slung his rifle over his shoulder and hung his helmet on a small hook on his belt. Everything he needed was attached, such as his gas mask or his special glasses. After checking his ammunition pouches, he quietly left the barrack. Outside, mud and ice crunched under his boots.
He took a lighter out of one of his jacket pockets and a cigarette out of the other. He lit it and took a short drag before he slightly opened the door. In the last week, he had to come up with quite a bit to wake up the people under his supervision. He no longer used the preset alarm clock because it mostly didn't work and only a faint hiss came from the speakers.
"Shall I wake them?" Cohren turned around and saw Foreman Nemic approaching him.
"Yes," replied Cohren.
"With what do you want to try it this time?"
Before he could answer, the door opened and Harris, Craith, and a few others came towards him already fully dressed.
"Good morning," said Craith.
"What did you wake up to?" asked Cohren.
"Well, first of all, we didn't feel like waiting to see what you'd come up with today. And secondly, the frontline troops, who rise first, get to choose the morning ration," one of the men, Ravik, replied. "And you know how bad the food can be."
"Good point, Sergeant," Cohren said. He reached in and pressed a button. A loud, shrill alarm sounded in the barracks. Inside, he heard faint cursing and people rushing around.
"Man, Valturi," said Nemic. "One would think they've learned by now to wake up at the same time as you."
"Well, my people from the training camp have learned it," Cohren replied and pointed at Harris, Craith, and Ravik. "However, the unit and platoon leaders also know that they have to stand in front of their units."
Seconds later, the rest of the company emerged. They had everything they needed, from personal belongings to necessary equipment. Some of the newer recruits looked confused, while others seemed annoyed.
"Good morning", Cohren said cheerfully.
"With all due respect, sir, why do you have to wake us up like this?", a sergeant of the shock troops asked.
"Because the regular alarms are crap and because Daybreak does not sleep", said Cohren.
“Pack up all your personal belongings,” Cohren continued. As a lieutenant colonel and the company's executive officer, he was responsible for overseeing and supporting the company, along with the company commander, Captain Boradin Shaw. “We won't be coming back here. Sergeant and lieutenants, you and your teams have 15 minutes to do a final check and pack up the daily rations.”
The members of the Exodus Company quickly dispersed. They were part of the second Assault Brigade Division, Second Army. Before they were merged, they were two companies, Cohort and Dagger. The company was divided, and that was the main reason why Cohren felt mixed emotions regarding his promotion to lieutenant colonel.
Cohren and Nemic, the leader of the first wave, walked side by side in the glow of the many generator-powered lamps of the forward operating base. Most had red-tinted glass to avoid being discovered by enemy bombers. Daybreak had resorted to Wild-Weasel attacks from the air and ground to counter them.
"A new day and a new task for the Hellhounds," Nemic said with a dry laugh. "Where are they sending us?"
"A forward deployment base outside Ianlos. We'll support the ground attack," Cohren replied and pulled on his cigarette. He blamed Craith in part for starting him on smoking, but a year in service changed a man, so he said nothing.
"Shit. It's only getting worse at the front", Nemic muttered. "All the news reports say: 'Support the war efforts. Send aid to the Kurgan Front.' What about aid for the Howland Front?"
"Amen, brother," Cohren said, snubbing the remains of his cigarette into the mud. "At least we're going off with the first armed train and don't have to run. Captain Shaw should already be there."
"Has Shaw made a lift clear to us?", Nemic asked a bit surprised.
"Yes. To be honest, he's not as bad as I thought. Not particularly friendly, but you can put up with him."
Cohren raised his thumb and index finger to his laryngoscope microphone and put on his backpack while doing so. "All units of the Exodus Company will gather at Fuhrpark West when they are finished. We will break out with the first armed column at 0500."
He received answers from the squad leaders in a second-by-second rhythm. Haris, Craith and Ravik were low-ranking non-commissioned officers when they all came here. The four had been close friends since their return to Earth. Cohren had the feeling that he had known them forever, although it had been at most two years. They were squad leaders, but Craith had been leading the second platoon for a week, after the previous leader was discharged due to medical reasons, after a Daybreak sniper had shot him.
On their way to the vehicle park, Cohren and Nemic spotted a group of about eight Kronos tanks and four infantry fighting vehicles. Their crew was running around, making sure their machines were combat-ready. Cohren quickly spotted Captain Boradin Shaw, speaking with the commander of the armed unit. As they drew closer, Shaw looked over at them and came towards them, as always with an expressionless face.
"Lieutenant Nemic... Lieutenant Valturi..." He said, Cohren was slower, while looking at Cohren's pistol holster and then looking up again. "The company is ready, I assume?"
